<header class="header">
  <h1>When to Start Tomatoes in Zone 3</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    Zone 3 is short-season — frost dates determine everything.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>In most Zone 3 locations, tomatoes should be started indoors 6–8 weeks before your average last spring frost.</strong>
    Because the frost-free window is short, precise timing is critical to maximize harvest.
  </p>

  <p>
    To calculate your exact indoor start and transplant dates,
    use the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a>
    based on your local frost dates.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Direct Answer</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Start tomato seeds indoors about 6–8 weeks before your last spring frost date in Zone 3.</strong>
    Transplant only after frost risk has passed and nighttime lows stay above 50°F (10°C).
  </p>

  <p>
    In many Zone 3 areas, this means starting seeds in late March or April
    for transplanting in late May or early June — but your frost date determines the real window.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Zone 3 Requires Precision</h2>

  <p>
    USDA Zone 3 typically experiences:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Average last spring frost: late May to early June</li>
    <li>Average first fall frost: early to mid-September</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Comparable cold regions in Canada follow similar timelines.
  </p>

  <p>
    The frost-free window may be only 90–110 days.
    Delays reduce harvest opportunity quickly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Tomato Timing Requirements</h2>

  <p>
    Tomatoes need:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>6–8 weeks indoors before transplant</li>
    <li>Nighttime temperatures above 50°F (10°C)</li>
    <li>Soil temperatures near 60°F (16°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Transplanting into repeated cool nights can permanently delay flowering.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Counting Back from Frost Dates</h2>

  <p>
    The most reliable method is:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Identify your average last spring frost date.</li>
    <li>Count backward 6–8 weeks for indoor seed starting.</li>
    <li>Monitor nighttime lows before transplanting.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Frost dates matter more than zone labels.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Choosing the Right Varieties for Zone 3</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select early-maturing varieties (55–70 days)</li>
    <li>Avoid very long-season heirlooms</li>
    <li>Consider determinate varieties for faster harvest</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short-season climates, early maturity increases success.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What If You Start Too Early?</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Seedlings may become leggy indoors</li>
    <li>Plants may outgrow containers before transplant time</li>
    <li>Cold weather delays outdoor planting</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If seedlings are growing too fast, see
    <a href="/guides/starting-seeds-too-early/">Starting Seeds Too Early</a>
    for management strategies.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What If You Start Too Late?</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Harvest may occur near first fall frost</li>
    <li>Total yield may decrease</li>
    <li>Long-season varieties may not mature fully</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Early varieties can still succeed even with a slightly delayed start.
  </p>
</section>

